-- Sensitive Index Climbs as Earnings Improve India's Economic Growth Outlook
-- B y   H e m a l   S a v a i
-- 2010-11-03T04:49:24Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-03/sensitive-index-climbs-as-earnings-improve-india-s-economic-growth-outlook.html
India’s stock rose, with the
benchmark index set for a three-week high, as improved corporate
earnings boosted the outlook for economic growth amid surging
inflows from overseas funds.  SpiceJet Ltd. , a discount carrier part-owned by billionaire
Kalanithi Maran, gained 1.3 percent after turning to a second-
quarter profit from a year-earlier loss.  Fortis Healthcare Ltd. 
climbed 2.2 percent after boosting profit more than fivefold.
 Oil & Natural Gas Corp. , the country’s biggest energy explorer,
advanced 0.4 percent after the Economic Times said its in talks
for an Australian acquisition.  The Bombay Stock Exchange’s Sensitive Index, or  Sensex ,
gained 174.23, or 0.9 percent, to 20,519.92 at 10:03 a.m. in
Mumbai. The gauge is extending this year’s best performance
among the world’s 10 biggest markets after India’s central bank
yesterday said the chance of further policy tightening in the
“immediate future is relatively low” following the sixth
increase in interest rates this year.  “The earnings growth rally continues as there was no major
surprises from the Reserve Bank,” said  Kishor Ostwal , managing
director of CNI Research (India) Ltd., a publicly traded
equities research provider in Mumbai.  The S&P CNX  Nifty  Index on the National Stock Exchange rose
0.9 percent to 6,171.75. The  BSE 200 Index  increased 0.9 percent
to 2,611.  Overseas Funds  Overseas  investors  bought a net  55.2 billion rupees  ($1.24
billion) of Indian equities on Nov. 1, extending this year’s
record inflows to 1.194 trillion rupees, according to data on
the  website  of the Securities and Exchange Board of India.  SpiceJet climbed 1.3 percent to 89.3 rupees after posting
second-quarter profit of 101.1 million rupees ($2.3 million),
compared with a loss of 1.01 billion rupees a year earlier. The
New Delhi-based company also said it will spend $900 million on
buying as many as 30 Bombardier Inc. aircraft as it works to
more than double its fleet in about three years.  Fortis Healthcare , India’s largest hospital operator by
market value, added 2.2 percent to 167.6 rupees after second-
quarter profit surged more than fivefold to 747.8 million
rupees.  Oil & Natural Gas gained 0.4 percent to 1,335.1 rupees.
India’s largest petroleum exploration company is in talks to
acquire a 25 percent stake in Australia’s Advent Energy for
about $1 billion, the Economic Times reported, citing two
unidentified officials with knowledge of the discussions.  To contact the reporter on this story:
